00:22:04,373 --> 00:22:07,123
- What's the problem here?
- Her mom called the OPO about

502
00:22:07,193 --> 00:22:10,377
- donating her organs, and then she backed off.
- Why?

503
00:22:10,446 --> 00:22:13,314
She can't accept the diagnosis.

504
00:22:13,382 --> 00:22:16,334
Is there any chance that
something good can come of this?

505
00:22:16,402 --> 00:22:19,052
Yes, so many people could
receive her other organs, too.

506
00:22:19,121 --> 00:22:21,305
If the family can be
made to face the truth.

507
00:22:21,374 --> 00:22:23,324
Want me to speak to them?

508
00:22:23,392 --> 00:22:24,324
-No. -No. -No.

509
00:22:24,393 --> 00:22:26,304
- Then you speak to them.
- I can't.

510
00:22:26,328 --> 00:22:29,129
Not anymore. No
doctor whose patient

511
00:22:29,215 --> 00:22:31,160
could benefit from an organ
donation can make the case

512
00:22:31,184 --> 00:22:32,477
to a family to
withdraw life support.

513
00:22:32,501 --> 00:22:34,735
It's a hard and fast
rule, and a good one.

514
00:22:34,804 --> 00:22:37,220
The hospital, on the
other hand, could step in.

515
00:22:41,744 --> 00:22:43,310
Ugh.

516
00:22:43,379 --> 00:22:46,130
Before you say anything,
I'm not here to argue.

517
00:22:46,199 --> 00:22:48,165
I have a solution.

518
00:22:48,234 --> 00:22:49,966
You have one minute. Go.

519
00:22:50,035 --> 00:22:53,687
There's a brain-dead patient
in the ICU. Chloe Gellar.

520
00:22:53,755 --> 00:22:55,300
Her heart could
save Micah's life,

521
00:22:55,324 --> 00:22:57,335
and you are the only
person I can think of

522
00:22:57,359 --> 00:23:00,094
who can convince the
mother to withdraw life support.

523
00:23:00,162 --> 00:23:03,463
So... so your solution
is to have me walk in

524
00:23:03,549 --> 00:23:06,366
and ask a grieving
mother to unplug her child?

525
00:23:06,435 --> 00:23:07,801
Her child is gone.

526
00:23:07,870 --> 00:23:09,514
- The answer's no.
- No one is better

527
00:23:09,538 --> 00:23:11,138
at communicating than you.

528
00:23:11,224 --> 00:23:12,668
Thanks for the
compliment, but no.

529
00:23:12,692 --> 00:23:14,775
Chloe's organs would
save so many lives.

530
00:23:14,844 --> 00:23:17,177
You know, humanitarian
considerations aside,

531
00:23:17,245 --> 00:23:19,129
to force a mother's hand

532
00:23:19,198 --> 00:23:21,198
- would risk a lawsuit.
- So Chloe stays

533
00:23:21,267 --> 00:23:23,011
on life support in
our ICU indefinitely?

534
00:23:23,035 --> 00:23:26,303
If her family can
handle it financially, yes.

535
00:23:26,372 --> 00:23:28,216
In other words, it's all
about the bottom line.

536
00:23:28,240 --> 00:23:30,157
You would gladly step in

537
00:23:30,226 --> 00:23:31,686
if Chastain weren't
making 100 grand a week

538
00:23:31,710 --> 00:23:33,438
on Chloe's
gold-plated insurance.

539
00:23:33,462 --> 00:23:36,113
The whole world is
about the bottom line.

540
00:23:42,455 --> 00:23:44,938
Your white blood cell
count is improving, Lily,

541
00:23:45,007 --> 00:23:46,652
but still a bit lower
than we'd like to see.

542
00:23:46,676 --> 00:23:48,553
I think you need to
stay here a little longer.

543
00:23:48,577 --> 00:23:52,145
No, please, Dr. Pravesh.
I just want to go home.

544
00:23:52,214 --> 00:23:54,181
Dr. Hunter already
said that I could.

545
00:23:54,250 --> 00:23:56,278
I'm not sure she's seen
your most recent numbers.

546
00:23:56,302 --> 00:23:58,280
Your immune system is
still badly compromised, Lily.

547
00:23:58,304 --> 00:24:00,115
You could easily get
another infection and

548
00:24:00,139 --> 00:24:02,251
- end up back in the ER again.
- And that's a huge risk

549
00:24:02,275 --> 00:24:04,408
with leukemia and what
brought you to the ER

550
00:24:04,477 --> 00:24:06,254
- in the first place.
- How we doing in here?

551
00:24:06,278 --> 00:24:08,646
Dr. Hunter, hi!

552
00:24:08,714 --> 00:24:10,431
How you feeling, darling?

553
00:24:10,499 --> 00:24:12,549
Better. Really, so much better.

554
00:24:12,618 --> 00:24:15,018
Well, no fever.

555
00:24:15,087 --> 00:24:16,481
- She did have one this morning.
- Exactly.

556
00:24:16,505 --> 00:24:18,350
That's why I'm trying
to get her out of here.

557
00:24:18,374 --> 00:24:20,034
Lily's more likely to
get another infection

558
00:24:20,058 --> 00:24:21,859
here than she would be at home.

559
00:24:21,927 --> 00:24:25,546
One in seven patients end up
with a hospital-based infection.

560
00:24:25,614 --> 00:24:28,515
People on chemo are most at
risk for everything from the flu

561
00:24:28,584 --> 00:24:32,268
- to MRSA.
- That's why I get my chemo at Dr. Hunter's clinic.

562
00:24:32,338 --> 00:24:34,355
Makes sense.

563
00:24:34,423 --> 00:24:36,101
It does, doesn't it?

564
00:24:36,125 --> 00:24:37,457
Excuse me.

565
00:24:37,526 --> 00:24:39,304
I haven't had the
chance to thank you

566
00:24:39,328 --> 00:24:41,323
for taking such good
care of my patient.

567
00:24:41,347 --> 00:24:44,131
- Of course.
- Wow. That's high praise.

568
00:24:44,199 --> 00:24:46,233
She doesn't trust
anyone but Conrad.

569
00:24:46,302 --> 00:24:50,253
Well, now I can
trust Dr. Pravesh, too.

570
00:24:50,323 --> 00:24:52,323
<i>And back in the day,</i>

571
00:24:52,357 --> 00:24:54,419
of course, we had no
way to retract skin flaps

572
00:24:54,443 --> 00:24:56,342
without holding your arms

573
00:24:56,411 --> 00:24:59,379
in an extremely uncomfortable
position for hours at a time

574
00:24:59,448 --> 00:25:03,216
until I invented... this
automatic retractor,

575
00:25:03,285 --> 00:25:05,569
which the company
named the "Bell."

576
00:25:05,621 --> 00:25:06,932
Out of modesty,

577
00:25:06,956 --> 00:25:09,036
of course, I demurred,
but they insisted.

578
00:25:09,091 --> 00:25:11,291
Dr. Bell, can I speak
with you a moment?

579
00:25:11,360 --> 00:25:13,827
Of course. How is
Congressman Dunlap?

580
00:25:13,896 --> 00:25:16,297
Well, there was a complication
with his pre-op tests.

581
00:25:16,365 --> 00:25:19,950
- That's concerning.
- And it appears when he fell,

582
00:25:20,019 --> 00:25:23,170
he fractured a rib,
lacerated his spleen.

583
00:25:23,238 --> 00:25:24,315
We can still do the transplant,

584
00:25:24,339 --> 00:25:26,523
but he'll need a
splenectomy first.

585
00:25:26,592 --> 00:25:28,842
And your outcomes
after splenectomy

586
00:25:28,911 --> 00:25:31,595
set the national standard.

587
00:25:31,647 --> 00:25:33,758
Can we count on you to scrub
in with the transplant team?

588
00:25:33,782 --> 00:25:36,516
I'd love to.

589
00:25:36,585 --> 00:25:38,485
All right. Thank you.

590
00:25:53,051 --> 00:25:55,051
♪ ♪

591
00:26:12,821 --> 00:26:15,422
Well, you know,
when I was your age,

592
00:26:15,491 --> 00:26:17,569
we did not have this
technology to practice on.

593
00:26:19,628 --> 00:26:22,679
I used to practice making
stitches with my hands

594
00:26:22,748 --> 00:26:26,533
jammed inside a tin can, just
to simulate that tight body cavity.

595
00:26:26,619 --> 00:26:29,369
Could you back up?

596
00:26:29,438 --> 00:26:30,654
Your cologne.

597
00:26:38,047 --> 00:26:40,780
I came to offer
you an opportunity.

598
00:26:40,849 --> 00:26:43,383
I'm doing a splenectomy prior
to Dunlap's heart transplant,

599
00:26:43,452 --> 00:26:45,235
and I'll need to be quick

600
00:26:45,304 --> 00:26:47,515
with zero pancreatic injury
to keep his outcome in line

601
00:26:47,539 --> 00:26:49,038
with my past successes,

602
00:26:49,107 --> 00:26:51,708
and you are welcome to observe

603
00:26:51,777 --> 00:26:54,578
and possibly even assist.

604
00:26:57,666 --> 00:27:00,033
You blackmailed me.

605
00:27:00,102 --> 00:27:01,802
You wouldn't help me get my visa

606
00:27:01,871 --> 00:27:04,082
unless I did the robotic surgery
you were supposed to do.

607
00:27:04,106 --> 00:27:07,875
Then... you took all the credit.

608
00:27:09,495 --> 00:27:13,030
I'm never saving your ass again.

609
00:27:22,341 --> 00:27:23,574
How's Mitch doing?

610
00:27:23,642 --> 00:27:25,442
He's not dead yet.

611
00:27:25,511 --> 00:27:26,877
Wait. What do you mean?

612
00:27:26,946 --> 00:27:28,623
Were there
complications in surgery?

613
00:27:28,647 --> 00:27:30,887
The clot was extensive.
I'm monitoring his vitals.

614
00:27:30,916 --> 00:27:32,928
I'll give him another
arterial blood gas in an hour

615
00:27:32,952 --> 00:27:35,719
and adjust his ventilator, but
he's not out of the woods yet.

616
00:27:51,820 --> 00:27:53,298
I couldn't discharge
him, Conrad.

617
00:27:53,322 --> 00:27:54,554
He's getting steadily worse.

618
00:27:54,623 --> 00:27:56,589
I can barely feel his pulse.

619
00:27:56,676 --> 00:27:58,758
His hands and feet are cold.

620
00:27:58,827 --> 00:28:02,345
I can't... lie down.

621
00:28:02,414 --> 00:28:04,748
When I do...

622
00:28:04,800 --> 00:28:06,111
- it feels like I'm drowning.
- Your lungs are

623
00:28:06,135 --> 00:28:07,496
building up with fluid,
because your heart

624
00:28:07,520 --> 00:28:08,846
is struggling to
pump efficiently.

625
00:28:08,870 --> 00:28:12,455
- I'm scared.
- Oh, you got

626
00:28:12,508 --> 00:28:13,684
to hold onto that
faith of yours, Micah.

627
00:28:13,708 --> 00:28:15,008
You got to stay strong.

628
00:28:15,094 --> 00:28:17,695
I don't know... if I can.

629
00:28:17,763 --> 00:28:20,731
Where's my miracle, Dr. Hawkins?

630
00:28:23,402 --> 00:28:24,601
I'll find one.

631
00:28:35,898 --> 00:28:37,998
There you are.

632
00:28:38,066 --> 00:28:39,644
We're running out of time.
They're prepping Dunlap

633
00:28:39,668 --> 00:28:41,530
- for surgery in an hour.
- I know.

634
00:28:41,554 --> 00:28:44,922
- What are you doing?
- Nothing you need to know about.

635
00:28:45,774 --> 00:28:47,924
Who's Samuel Poole?

636
00:28:51,647 --> 00:28:54,180
Whatever you're
doing, don't do it.

637
00:29:05,811 --> 00:29:08,311
Hey, Noni.

638
00:29:08,380 --> 00:29:10,881
You are looking
lovely today, as always.

639
00:29:10,950 --> 00:29:12,649
Pretty lovely yourself.

640
00:29:12,718 --> 00:29:14,618
What is it? What...?

641
00:29:15,770 --> 00:29:17,888
Those are cute earrings.

642
00:29:17,956 --> 00:29:20,690
So, um, I need a favor.

643
00:29:20,760 --> 00:29:21,992
Name it.

644
00:29:22,044 --> 00:29:23,964
Can you get me
two blood samples?

645
00:29:24,029 --> 00:29:25,573
I have to verify they
weren't hemolyzed

646
00:29:25,597 --> 00:29:27,898
in case that messed with
the analysis, and I would

647
00:29:27,967 --> 00:29:29,093
consider it a special favor

648
00:29:29,117 --> 00:29:30,695
if you would do it
for me while I wait?

649
00:29:30,719 --> 00:29:32,819
Anything for you, Conrad.

650
00:29:32,888 --> 00:29:35,105
Trip Dunlap, the congressman?

651
00:29:35,174 --> 00:29:38,091
- Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.
- And Samuel Poole.

652
00:29:38,159 --> 00:29:40,594
Okay.

653
00:30:15,681 --> 00:30:17,163
All good, Noni.

654
00:30:19,067 --> 00:30:21,751
- Thanks.
- Mm-hmm.

655
00:30:26,741 --> 00:30:28,925
These aren't
consistent with Trip's

656
00:30:28,994 --> 00:30:30,722
blood tests you
ran earlier today.

657
00:30:30,746 --> 00:30:33,113
No, the incompatibility
is a rare one

658
00:30:33,182 --> 00:30:34,625
that didn't show
up the first time.

659
00:30:34,649 --> 00:30:37,634
Randolph, this HLA
result means that...

660
00:30:37,703 --> 00:30:39,570
Oh, he'd have a life-threatening

661
00:30:39,621 --> 00:30:41,633
immune reaction if exposed
to this particular donor heart.

662
00:30:41,657 --> 00:30:44,040
The heart would be
destroyed in the process.

663
00:30:44,109 --> 00:30:46,776
We both know this heart
won't work for Dunlap,

664
00:30:46,845 --> 00:30:49,612
but can, however, still
work for Micah Stevens,

665
00:30:49,681 --> 00:30:52,582
the patient who was supposed
to get it in the first place.

666
00:30:52,650 --> 00:30:54,762
And Stevens doesn't
have the same HLA issue?

667
00:30:54,786 --> 00:30:56,803
- No, he doesn't.
- Hmm.

668
00:30:56,871 --> 00:30:58,388
This is quite a save.

669
00:30:58,456 --> 00:30:59,868
What inspired you
to run the test again?

670
00:30:59,892 --> 00:31:01,132
Well, I can't take the credit.

671
00:31:01,159 --> 00:31:02,642
Conrad Hawkins asked me to do it

672
00:31:02,711 --> 00:31:06,830
as a precaution, which leaves
us with a pretty big problem.

673
00:31:06,898 --> 00:31:09,800
The press is outside waiting
to report on Dunlap's surgery.

674
00:31:09,868 --> 00:31:11,668
He's in critical condition.

675
00:31:11,737 --> 00:31:13,248
Who's going to go
out and tell them

676
00:31:13,272 --> 00:31:15,739
we don't have a
heart for him anymore?

677
00:31:19,695 --> 00:31:21,728
Nobody.

678
00:31:26,468 --> 00:31:28,735
♪ ♪

679
00:31:37,179 --> 00:31:38,811
To me, the people who...

680
00:31:38,898 --> 00:31:42,015
He could talk a
dog off a meat truck.

681
00:31:42,084 --> 00:31:43,700
Will see the gift.

682
00:31:43,769 --> 00:31:45,730
He's finally helping
us do the right thing.

683
00:31:45,754 --> 00:31:49,656
For all the wrong reasons.

684
00:31:49,725 --> 00:31:53,760
♪ ♪

685
00:31:59,384 --> 00:32:02,852
I hear Chloe's mother
agreed to donate her organs.

686
00:32:02,921 --> 00:32:04,220
That's nice work, Bell.

687
00:32:04,289 --> 00:32:06,100
No, I believe the
credit's all yours.

688
00:32:06,124 --> 00:32:09,475
You found a patient with
an HLA incompatibility and

689
00:32:09,544 --> 00:32:11,605
the same blood type as Dunlap's,
you switched the samples,

690
00:32:11,629 --> 00:32:13,707
and then you told Peterson
to run the test again.

691
00:32:13,731 --> 00:32:15,543
- Mm. Prove it.
- I'll have them check the vials

692
00:32:15,567 --> 00:32:19,169
- for fingerprints, and then I'll run the DNA.
- Go for it.

693
00:32:19,238 --> 00:32:21,266
- Micah will already have his heart.
- And you

694
00:32:21,290 --> 00:32:23,790
will never practice
medicine again.

695
00:32:26,979 --> 00:32:30,880
Two patients are getting
organs, two lives saved.

696
00:32:30,949 --> 00:32:33,749
If you want to dirty this win
with a scandal, be my guest.

697
00:32:35,804 --> 00:32:38,355
I don't.

698
00:32:38,424 --> 00:32:40,590
I'll do nothing.

699
00:32:43,228 --> 00:32:45,829
If I get what I want in return.

700
00:32:51,436 --> 00:32:53,603
- Hi.
- Hi.

701
00:32:53,672 --> 00:32:56,056
- Good luck, Micah.
- Good luck, Micah.

702
00:32:58,326 --> 00:33:00,894
- Mina?
- What's up?

703
00:33:00,963 --> 00:33:02,573
I have to scrub in
for Micah's surgery.

704
00:33:02,597 --> 00:33:04,342
I want you to take
Bell's offer instead.

705
00:33:04,366 --> 00:33:06,917
Don't let him screw up the
congressman's splenectomy.

706
00:33:06,985 --> 00:33:10,220
Why would you, of all people,
want me to help HODAD, the hands

707
00:33:10,289 --> 00:33:12,600
- of death and destruction?
- It's not about helping him.

708
00:33:12,624 --> 00:33:14,768
I'm thinking about the best
way to advance your career.

709
00:33:14,792 --> 00:33:17,410
Bell's still the most
requested surgeon at Chastain.

710
00:33:17,496 --> 00:33:19,006
He gets the most
interesting cases,

711
00:33:19,030 --> 00:33:20,258
and he trusts you to
operate beside him.

712
00:33:20,282 --> 00:33:22,276
You need the practice.
Win-win situation.

713
00:33:22,300 --> 00:33:24,000
Congressman Dunlap,

714
00:33:24,069 --> 00:33:25,896
he doesn't deserve to be
harmed by a botched splenectomy.

715
00:33:25,920 --> 00:33:27,031
You could
potentially save a life.

716
00:33:27,055 --> 00:33:28,975
Isn't that what
we're here to do?

717
00:33:30,075 --> 00:33:33,076
You had me at
"advance my career."

718
00:33:41,369 --> 00:33:43,303
♪ <i>Seconds</i> ♪

719
00:33:43,371 --> 00:33:46,239
♪ <i>Ticking off the clock</i> ♪

720
00:33:46,308 --> 00:33:47,941
♪ <i>Counting</i> ♪

721
00:33:48,010 --> 00:33:51,361
♪ <i>Down to when I walk</i> ♪

722
00:33:51,430 --> 00:33:54,981
♪ <i>It's easier to
go than to stay</i> ♪

723
00:33:55,067 --> 00:33:57,833
♪ <i>Just watch me
take that flicker</i> ♪

724
00:33:57,902 --> 00:34:00,653
♪ <i>To flame</i> ♪

725
00:34:00,722 --> 00:34:02,589
♪ <i>Sometimes...</i> ♪

726
00:34:02,657 --> 00:34:05,157
Dr. Okafor. Now, my approach
to this complex procedure

727
00:34:05,226 --> 00:34:07,226
will die with me if
it isn't passed on

728
00:34:07,295 --> 00:34:09,390
to the next generation.
